es containing '..', '/', or path separators\",\n    \"Add explicit allowlist validation for command-line arguments before processing - validate command names and known flags only\",\n    \"Implement message protocol versioning and strict schema validation in socketConnection - reject messages that don't match expected schema\",\n    \"Enforce restrictive file permissions on daemon directory (~700 or owner-only) - document that daemon profiles directory must not be world-writable\",\n    \"Add logging/auditing for session file operations - log when session configs are loaded or modified\",\n    \"Use Object.freeze() on config objects after loading to prevent runtime mutations\",\n    \"Consider using zod, joi, or similar for runtime schema validation of all external data (JSON configs, socket messages)\"\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n## Key Findings\n\n**Good Security Practices Found:**\n- ✅ No hardcoded secrets or API keys\n- ✅ No SQL injection risks (no database code)\n- ✅ No XSS vulnerabilities (backend/CLI library, not web app)\n- ✅ Proper error handling with try/catch blocks\n- ✅ Safe use of Node.js APIs (fs.promises, path.join())\n- ✅ Socket communication uses JSON with error handling\n- ✅ File paths use `path.join()` which normalizes separators\n\n**Areas of Concern:**\n- Minimal input validation on CLI arguments and session configs\n- Path traversal risks exist but require prior filesystem access\n- No schema validation for JSON configurations\n- Missing integrity checks on inter-process communication\n\n**Context:** This is a well-established browser automation library (Microsoft Playwright). The low risk score reflects that this is infrastructure code with proper foundational security, not web-facing application code.\n",
